# Tyre Pulse – Complete UI UX Redesign, Tyre Man PWA Architecture Review & Onboarding Experience

You are no longer acting as a software developer only.

You are acting as:

* Principal Product Designer
* Senior UX Researcher
* Enterprise SaaS Architect
* Fleet Management Domain Expert
* Mobile UX Specialist
* PWA Specialist
* React & Vite Technical Lead
* Design System Architect
* Accessibility Expert (WCAG 2.2 AA)
* Frontend Performance Engineer

This is **not** a cosmetic redesign.

Your task is to audit the entire Tyre Pulse project from a real user's perspective and redesign the experience so it feels like a premium enterprise fleet management platform.

Do not assume anything.

First understand the entire project before changing anything.

---

# STEP 1 – Read Everything First

Before writing code or making UI changes:

Read and understand every existing project document, including but not limited to:

* Tyre Man documentation
* Mobile application documentation
* PRDs
* UI documents
* Database documentation
* User role documentation
* Workflow documentation
* Business logic
* Fleet workflow
* Inspection workflow
* Dashboard workflow
* Permissions
* Country settings
* Multi-tenant logic
* Existing design system
* Existing mobile screens
* Existing React components

If documentation is incomplete, inspect the codebase and derive the correct workflow.

Do NOT redesign blindly.

Understand how users actually work.

---

# STEP 2 – Understand Every User

Study every user role.

Understand:

* what they do
* what they see
* what they never need
* what slows them down
* what information they require most often

Examples include:

* Tyre Man
* Workshop Staff
* Fleet Supervisor
* Fleet Manager
* PMV Manager
* Operations Manager
* Store Keeper
* Administrator

Every interface should only expose the features that role needs.

No unnecessary screens.

No unnecessary buttons.

No unnecessary menus.

---

# STEP 3 – Build the Tyre Man PWA

The Android application is still under preparation for Google Play.

Meanwhile build a dedicated Tyre Man PWA using the existing React/Vite application.

Do NOT create a generic web app.

The PWA should feel like a native Android application.

Reuse existing mobile screens wherever possible.

Reuse:

* components
* authentication
* APIs
* Supabase
* business logic
* permissions
* inspection flows

Do not duplicate code unnecessarily.

The Tyre Man PWA should include only field operations.

No management dashboards.

No analytics.

No administration.

No unnecessary complexity.

---

# STEP 4 – Match Existing Mobile Application

The Tyre Man PWA should look and behave almost exactly like the existing mobile application.

Reuse:

* layouts
* navigation
* icons
* spacing
* forms
* buttons
* typography
* interaction patterns

The experience should remain consistent across:

Web

PWA

Native Android

Future iOS

The user should immediately understand every version.

